</p>
<p>
<seg id="3">There are people for whom their work - a hell, and others literally work in a hell.</seg>
<seg id="4">Among them Anto Vidzhaya, one of 400 miners who earn on life by sulfur production in Kavakh-Idzhen's located in the east of the Indonesian island of Java the volcano.</seg>
<seg id="5">Every day Anto goes down on the bottom of a crater where the sulphurous gas rising from depths of Earth, stiffens at contact with air.</seg>
<seg id="6">Having broken away huge pieces of the sulfur which gross weight can reach 70 kg, it puts them in two bamboo baskets, shoulders baskets and bears them upward on the steep stony road.</seg>
<seg id="7">To the volcano top which height makes 2.386 meters, only 250 meters, however are required to emaciated loaders more than 40 minutes to rise at a snail's pace, hardly keeping balance and carefully groping the road not to stumble and to fall from break.</seg>
<seg id="8">They know that one wrong move can cost them life as it happened to one tourist from France which broke a few years ago from Kavakh-Idzhen's rocks.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="9">Miners from Kavakh-Idzhen earn 5 eurocents for each kilogram of sulfur which extract</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="10">Having appeared above, they force the way through between tourists who photograph them as though they were monkeys from circus and, wearily bearing heavy baskets, three kilometers to scales which the mining company arranged slightly above, at the height of 1.850 meters walk.</seg>
<seg id="11">It is a question of PT Kandy of Ngrimbi, the enterprise which operates since 1960 this volcano and, better and not to tell, the workers to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 eurocents) for each kilogram of sulfur.</seg>
<seg id="12">Then it sells it for 10.000 rupees (83 eurocents) to petrochemical productions, after all this mineral is widespread in an everyday life and is used for production of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for sugar bleaching.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="13">"As norm is carrying of 70 kilograms, we earn about 46.000 rupees (3,8 euros) for each trip", - explains us Anto who usually carries out three daily carryings.</seg>
<seg id="14">It spends three hours for each of them and at the end feels broken, however they allow it to save up 138.000 rupees (11,5 euros) by the end of day.</seg>
<seg id="15">Though it seems a hardly anything for such inhuman effort, it is three times more than that it would earn in the field.</seg>
<seg id="16">"The day payment to miners is very high by local standards where 15.000 rupees (1,2 euros) pay for gathering coffee a day and average monthly earnings is equal to two million rupees (167 euros)", - the loader who worked as the bricklayer at the tourist island of Bali earlier explains.</seg>
<seg id="17">There its salary made 75.000 rupees (6,2 euros) a day and the site wasn't such heavy, but Anto returned with the family to Banyyuvangi, small town near a volcano, for the weighty reason which in Indonesia is same shattering as sulfur: "I married the girl from Bali where one induist, and I brought her to Java that it accepted Islam".</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="18">Anto has an asthma, he labors for breath, constantly coughs, and at him слезятся eyes because of toxic gases</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="19">In the 27 years Anto spent three years, risking itself in Kavakh-Idzhen which sulfur already started affecting it despite existence of a mask and special glasses.</seg>
<seg id="20">It has an asthma, he labors for breath, constantly coughs, and at it слезятся eyes because of toxic gases which are emitted by a volcano.</seg>
<seg id="21">It is the price which he has to pay for achievement of the dream.</seg>
<seg id="22">"Two more years because I want to open shop will work or to study Spanish or French", - he promises in more than acceptable English.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="23">Punished by life, this pleasant and clever young man could be the tourist guide, the waiter or the porter in hotel, but instead it performs work of a mule.</seg>
<seg id="24">Sharing a dirty wooden hut with other porters, he gets up every day at two o'clock in the morning because sulfur doesn't cease to follow at night when its characteristic yellow color turns in blue and shines among a gloom.</seg>
<seg id="25">Throwing down a challenge to shadows, Anto goes down in a crater, shining itself the road with the small lamp connected to its helmet which he bought on the money.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="26">About 400 porters drag baskets with sulfur on the shoulders from a volcano bottom</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="27">Despite high profits, the mining company didn't mechanize sulfur production for economy of expenses and doesn't provide any equipment to porters who work for the account and with such deprivations.</seg>
<seg id="28">Actually, they don't receive even part from 30.000 rupees (2,5 euros) charge for photographing which, along with the entrance ticket for 15.000 rupees (1,2 euros), security guards of this reserve raise from tourists who come to photograph a volcano and its people mules.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="29">"This work for cattle, instead of for people", - declares to Badrusin, the thickset porter of 42 years who spent three decades since left college on Kavakh-Idzhen.</seg>
<seg id="30">Capable to lift to 110 kilograms, he assures that will suffer work "so much, how many will be able" because money for education of the three children aged from 18 till 10 years is necessary to it.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="31">I won't retire, I will die here because the volcano is all my life</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="32">Though sulfur burns a throat and burns down eyes when the wind suddenly changes and catches miners in the dense columns of a smoke leaving a volcano, they are so hardy that any doesn't complain of the serious illness... more serious, obviously, than their habitual trouble breathing, arthroses, knee pains and shoulder ulcers which were deformed under weight of baskets.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="33">Balancing with a basket on a back, Unaynik only can lift now 50 kilograms in the 53 years.</seg>
<seg id="34">Every day it and his companions take out 15 tons of sulfur from a volcano which three trucks transport on a warehouse in Tamansari, overcoming distance in 18 kilometers on a narrow track among thickets.</seg>
<seg id="35">"I won't retire, I will die here because the volcano is all my life", - Unaynik declares, widely opening a mouth in which there is no several teeth.</seg>
<seg id="36">From his five children, the senior, 30 years, too works with a sulfur carrier.</seg>
<seg id="37">Time passes, but poverty immortalizes from generation to generation one of the heaviest occupations in the world: in what human mules from Kavakh-Idzhen are engaged.</seg>
</p>
